text: I'm a big fan of predator. Ever since I was too young to watch it.  But I wish they change up the formula, here's my pitch:  What if... a Predator was a recurring character? Not a different predator that always loses, but a Predator that always wins..  Now before you go and write this off as stupid, think of Jason. Jason from the Friday the 13th films always comes back, and kills almost all the teens. He's essentially the main character since no one likes the teens. And that franchise was super successful.  So instead of highly advanced aliens who dedicate their lives to literally hunting aliens getting killed by any human... (danny glover.. im looking at you) make a recurring badass Predator who is tenacious as any hero. And find extremely creative ways for him to win. With maybe 1 or 2 survivors.

text: Making a guess based on the trailer and description because why not?  Hybrid vigor.  The Kaiju Predator is an engineered cross-breed not unlike a Liger (Lion/Tiger).  The gigantism may or may not be a deliberate effect of this.  And speaking of which, there may be other less happy "accidents" with this Extra-Large Slab of Ugly.  Like lowered resistance to microbes?  Yeah.  Of course, the thing with Predators is that they also carry nukes for self-destruct purposes.  That IS deliberate, and may be the real issue here: If "the hunt" is your culture, how do you deploy a planet-buster style of Weapon of Mass Destruction without being a coward engaged in push-button warfare?  Oh right, you breed an Unstable Extra-Large Slab of Ugly, shove a nuke up its butt, and infect it with every possible exo-disease you can scrounge, on the hunch that if the radiation release doesn't do it, the spread of randomly mutated diseases not native to planet just might.  Of course, it's overkill for what looks to be a cheap-to-generic reboot of a sci-fi-action franchise, but hey.  =))

text: Something interesting.  Predators are basically a metaphor for one version of a projection of our own species onto an "alien" race.  Like, think about it, since we have no proof of aliens.  Technically any "Alien" we imagine from a story is only a mere projection of our own human lives superimposed onto something "unknown" but even still, it's how "WE"  imagine an alien would think and behave, and that's only based around our own psychology of what we think would interest a super being like that.

text: It looks promising.  Sterling K Brown and Thomas Jane are two powerful actors in their own right and the rest of the cast seem very entertaining.  The Alien vs Predator (2004) was my favourite and will be a hard movie to better as the legendary Lance Henriksen was on his game portraying Charles Bishop Weyland, the ailing boss who funds the original exploration led by Sigourney Weaver.  The hero or rather heroine of the story was Sanaa Lathan who managed to play a really convincing if not reluctant master guide into the dangerous landscape of Antarctica who for the first time actually earned the respect of the lizard hunters who settle for nothing less than your head, we didn't see that one coming.  But it was set against a very interesting and intriguing backdrop, the pyramid.  I guess we can only wait and see what September 14th brings.  Looking forward to it.  Till then, take it easy folks. ‚ô•

text: Looks potentially worrying. This could really hurt what is essentially a golden and untapped franchise. So Predators have become deranged and are messing with their own DNA now? They're supposed to be cunning, sly, stealthy, mysterious hunters of worthy prey with a dark sense of humor and technology as mysterious as their motives. They're not supposed to be unhinged criminally insane psychopaths. They hunt because it's what they do culturally. Get the Lore right first, then write a decent story. The last decent movie was Predator 2 and that was almost 30 years ago.

text: If I was going to make a new Predator movie, I would say ok here are the ground rules: 1) You can't make it about some other creature or alter the predators to be larger or more lethal - that is cheap and not how you make a movie "better". 2) It must be Rated "R". 3) No puns or one-liners. 4) We must learn something new and interesting about the Predators, but you can't reveal everything, it can't contradict what we know, and it can't be the basis of the whole plot. 5) The hero must be intelligent and not make stupid decisions. 6) It can't be "personal" - the hero is doing what they are because they are a HERO - not because they want revenge, or are trapped and have no choice, or they didn't give a crap until it was their loved one in danger. A good person to sympathize with and care about. 7) It must be suspenseful, intelligent, intense, and creative. 8) No standard predictable 'Hollywood ending'. 9) It must be scientifically feasible within the sci-fi parameters already established. 10) It must have a diversity of pacing - some slow parts, character development, interspersed with action parts. It can't just be nonstop loud noises and action from start to finish where you couldn't care less about what happens.

text: WoW, another movie inspired by nerdy  comics with a Paul WS Anderson vibe ( beware the shuriken ). Predator was clearly an horrific primal creature with low intelligence (got trapped by boyscout tricks) and using such space hunting tech does not mean he is even able to craft it. In the first movie the creature is defined "sporty" by Dutch but it is clearly SARCASM...the woman was not the primary target in that moment because she was not armed, but she would have been just killed after Dutch. Predator has not honor at all...he has overconfidence on advanced tech to hunt stealthy and have fun on killing  peoples. Comics started all the nerdy things and we got "fancy chromed space samurais with honor code" willing to team up with humans or even accepting them in a "Yautja-KAI Dojo". Xenomorph received a similar treatment because in  Cameron movie was wiped and even defined by soldiers as a "space bug" but we all know how HARD the xeno body is...and marines are said to use special bullets to penetrate it...but NERD comic writers overplotted on few movie lines and we got the "Antlike space xeno with many colours\queens\shapes etc". A talented director like John Carpenter,Veroheven, Scott, Dante, Kubric would never accept to make an AVP movie or transform an horror movie in a silly comic action-comedy just to sell to a broad audience...but the nowadays casual dumb mass will even probably pay to watch a JAWS reboot with an upgraded superpowered shark in 4k...wtf i want 80's back

I doubt I'll bother with this even after it hits a streaming service. If they would re-release the original films for a full running and not just a one day only event I would absolutely be there, at least once, for every film. I'd imagine a lot of people would prefer big screen re-releases in place of all of these sub-par reboots and remakes.

text: One thing all of the sequels got wrong about the Predator is that they are supposed to be extremely skilled hunters. One important trait of a hunter is patience. In the original movie, the Predator would stalk and terrorize the soldiers without being properly seen until the end. Predator 2 was the movie that introduced the taunting and arrogant nature of them. I understand that they kill to test themselves and making the enemy angry probably makes things more interesting but i always saw the Predator as an "honorable" creature. They left multiple people alive during the movies and even showed great respect to those who defeated their kind so why portray them as genocidal maniacs? I hope the movie has more to it than the trailer.

text: Alright, just saw the movie tonight. AVOID AT ALL COSTS It's terrible. Awful. Worse than Predators, and that's hard to do. The CGI looks worse than it did in AVP, which is shocking.  They made fun of mental disorders throughout the ENTIRE movie. A few jokes of that sort are fine, and don't bother me, but they did it the ENTIRE film.  They tried too hard to be like the original, as well. Butchered lines from the original, tried to re-crate the "rag tag" band of soldiers, but horribly failed. I'd say the worst offender in this movie, by far, is how awful the effects were. I seriously don't think they were finished with them, but had to release the film. The blood has a weird 3D CGI look to it, both the human, and predator blood. The ships looked pretty bad, and the predators themselves looked pretty bad with their masks off.  Do NOT waste your time or money with this film. If you REALLY want to see it, wait until it comes out on streaming.

text: Haven't seen this yet, but I look forward to seeing it despite the mixed reviews to make up my own mind. Saw a few clips posted on YouTube, which impressed me, as you have finally... *FINALLY* included the Yautja dialogue. Quite frankly, if there's to be another Predator film, I would rather see the Predators themselves as central characters and jump more into their culture with much more dialogue between them, studying the humans etc.  The Predator franchise has come such a long way since the first film. The Predator isn't just a background villain anymore. In the wake of dozens and dozens of comic books, novels, games, maybe it's time to do a film, or even a short TV series of a few episodes, that focuses mostly and solely on the Predators themselves: hunts, traditions, honour, dishonour, clans, bloodlines... I'm sure a majority of Predator fans would be interested in possibly seeing this as opposed to the usual formula, which has been present in 3 of the 4 movies, as I've not seen this 4th instalment yet.
